article.description:
Taj McWilliams-Franklin scored 17 points as the Sun clinched the final postseason berth with a 72-62 victory that
eliminated Indiana from playoff contention.
article.headline: Sun finish season winning final 3 games
article.linkText: Connecticut tops Indiana for playoff berth
article.story:
INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- As the Connecticut players filed into the
locker room at halftime, many of their cell phones had the message
they were waiting for: Cleveland had won, meaning the only way the
Sun could make the playoffs was by winning.

"I felt like all day we needed to win," Sun coach Mike
Thibault said.

Taj McWilliams-Franklin scored 17 points as the Sun clinched
their first playoff berth with a 72-62 win over the Indiana Fever
on Monday night.

"It's not really about making the playoffs,"
McWilliams-Franklin said. "It's the way we came together the last
two weeks of the season that's special."

The Sun (18-16) are the No. 3 seed in the Eastern Conference and
will play No. 2 Charlotte. Top-seeded Detroit will play Cleveland.

The Sun could have made the playoffs with a loss if Cleveland
also lost to Charlotte. But the Rockers beat the Sting 75-66
forcing the Sun into a must-win situation.

"The reality is, we had to go out and do this for ourselves,"
Thibault said.

Nykesha Sales scored 14 points, Shannon Johnson had 12 and
Brooke Wyckoff 11 for the Sun.

Connecticut players raised their arms in triumph as they headed
off the court, listening to Fever coach Nell Fortner make brief
comments to the crowd on fan appreciation night.

For the second straight year, the Fever (16-18) needed a win on
the final game of the season to make the playoffs. Last year, they
won at Cleveland. This year, they missed the playoffs for the third
time in four seasons.

"It's hurting pretty bad," Tamika Catchings said. "We're
really disappointed in the way we lost."

Catchings, playing with stitches under her left eye after
reopening a wound on Saturday, scored 20 points, Natalie Williams
had 20 points and 10 rebounds and Kristen Rasmussen had 12 points.

Despite 31 percent shooting in the second half, the Fever tied
the game at 50 on a jumper by Catchings with 9:21 to play. But that
was the last time Indiana would have a share of the lead.

Wyckoff hit the go-ahead 3-pointer and McWilliams-Franklin also
added one during 9-0 run.

"We just ran out of gas," Fortner said. "We've got to keep
building and be stronger for next year."

The Fever shot 30 percent from the floor while the Sun shot 56
percent. McWilliams-Franklin was 7-for-11 from the floor and
Johnson, Wyckoff and Sales each missed only three attempts.

The WNBA changed its business model in October, ending central
ownership of teams and cutting ties that bound teams to NBA
franchises. Orlando and the league's Miami franchise folded and the
Utah franchise moved to San Antonio.

The Sun were purchased by the Mohegan Indian Tribe.
